{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:14:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:14:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12232"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12232"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.01,0.02,0.07,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114869"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4754"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96875"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"2283"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7558"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48550"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114869"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of worsening cough and shortness of breath. He has had a productive cough daily for about 10 years, which is now associated with haemoptysis. He has a 70 pack-year smoking history. His medical history includes arthritis and kidney stones. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Some hoarseness in his voice is evident. There is no cervical lymphadenopathy. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. A chest X-ray shows a 5 cm irregularly shaped mass in the right upper lobe near the hilum. CT chest confirms this finding. CT abdomen and pelvis shows no evidence of metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchoscopy with biopsy","Pulmonary function testing","Sputum cytology","PET scan","CT-guided biopsy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of lung cancer, including a long smoking history, chronic cough with recent haemoptysis, hoarseness (suggesting possible recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement), and radiological evidence of a central lung mass. The absence of cervical lymphadenopathy and abdominal metastases on CT does not exclude malignancy but suggests potentially localised disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step because the lesion is centrally located near the hilum. Modern techniques often employ endobronchial ultrasound-guided transbronchial needle aspiration (EBUS-TBNA), which provides excellent access to central and hilar lesions. This approach allows direct visualisation of the airways, assessment of endobronchial involvement, and tissue sampling for histological diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for peripheral lesions that are not accessible via bronchoscopy. Given the central location of this mass near the hilum, bronchoscopy is preferred as it avoids the risk of pneumothorax associated with percutaneous approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum cytology\u003C/strong\u003E has low sensitivity for diagnosing lung cancer and cannot provide the tissue architecture needed for accurate histological classification. When a more definitive diagnostic procedure like bronchoscopy is available, sputum cytology would not be the preferred initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan\u003C/strong\u003E is valuable for staging once a tissue diagnosis is confirmed. While the CT abdomen and pelvis has already excluded abdominal metastases, PET scanning would help identify other distant metastases and mediastinal lymph node involvement. However, tissue diagnosis must be obtained first to confirm malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function testing\u003C/strong\u003E is important for assessing operability if surgical resection is being considered. However, this assessment is premature before confirming the diagnosis histologically. The tissue diagnosis will determine whether the lesion is a primary lung cancer, metastasis from another source, or a benign process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bronchoscopy with biopsy is the most appropriate initial diagnostic step for centrally located lung masses.","Tissue diagnosis must be obtained before staging investigations in suspected lung cancer."],"references":["Collins LG, Haines C, Perkel R, Enck RE. Lung cancer: diagnosis and management. Am Fam Physician. 2007 Jan 1;75(1):56-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96875"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12232"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96875"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T11:55:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T11:56:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4754"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114869"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","